I was drawn to this particular gun because of the beautiful two-tone stock. It stands out among similar types of conversions. The bottom of the stock is sort of square, not round like most, so it shoots great off sand bags or other flat surfaces. I like how it feels in my hand.
Also important, the barrel length on this one remains the original 24". Most people cut this down to 21" when they make a sporter, but I like the extra velocity and accuracy you get with the 24" barrel. It also has a nice White Line Pachmayr recoil pad.
The gun has been drilled for scope mounts and is ready for you to add your rings and scope! The gun does have a few knicks and dings in the finish, but still very nice overall! The serial number dates the 1903 to 1922.
The bolt is stamped with an R in two places. One is a regular R, and the other is a stylized R (fatter legs). One on the bolt, and one on the underside of the bolt handle. I'm thinking it is an early Remington bolt? Also, the barrel is highly polished, so most barrel markings are gone. However, you can make out "8 22". It would have been 8-22, but the dash has been polished out. Most of the 8 remains and 22 is clearly visible. This dates the barrel to 1922 and the serial number to 1922. I measured the barrel diameter at the crown as .3025". This would be a 2.5 on a wear indicator.
I bet this gun would look nice sitting in your gun safe, or out in the field taking game!Cash only.  No trades.  Can meet in Fleming County or surrounding area (Bath, Rowan, Mason, Montgomery, etc.).  No haggling over price when meeting to conduct the transaction.  We will agree on price in advance and you will be able to inspect the item to make sure it is suitable and conduct the transaction.  Since this is a rifle, I can only conduct the transaction with a resident of KY who is legally able to purchase a rifle (18 and older).  You may be asked to produce ID to verify (please don't be offended, its just CYA).
